		<title>Applying Facio Behavioural, Part 4 &#8211; Gap Alignment</title>
		<link>http://facio.com/blog/2012/08/applying-facio-behavioural-part-4-gap-alignment-2/</link>
		<comments>http://facio.com/blog/2012/08/applying-facio-behavioural-part-4-gap-alignment-2/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 21 Aug 2012 12:00:55 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Dirk]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[behaviours]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Infovis]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://facio.com/?p=361</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>Continuing the series on analyzing Facio behavioural reports is the topic of Gap Alignment. This deals with a comparison of the difference between the self-actual and self-ideal with the others-actual and others-ideal. What you are looking for here is agreement &#8230; <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/08/applying-facio-behavioural-part-4-gap-alignment-2/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a></p><p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/08/applying-facio-behavioural-part-4-gap-alignment-2/">Applying Facio Behavioural, Part 4 &#8211; Gap Alignment</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Continuing the series on analyzing Facio behavioural reports is the topic of Gap Alignment. This deals with a comparison of the difference between the self-actual and self-ideal with the others-actual and others-ideal. What you are looking for here is agreement or disagreement in order to add nuance to other aspects of Facio Behavioural.</p>
<figure style="width: 300px;" class="alignleft"><a href="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/behaviour_task_completion.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-495" title="Facio Behaviours - Task Completion" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/behaviour_task_completion-300x184.jpg" alt="Facio Behaviours - Task Completion" width="300" height="184" />Click to view</a><br />
<figcaption>Even though others&#8217; see me as being far less deadline driven than I see myself, we all agree: I would benefit from being more early starting.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>While your conclusions and analysis may different depending on the degrees of difference in each case, in general, if both the self and others are reporting that they would ideally like to change in the same direction, this is a nice way to validate with the person that the change they would like to see in themselves is also identified by others. This is valuable because it is absolute: regardless of any of the other behavioural indicators, there is agreement that the person should probably be more of one thing and less of another. That development path is clear. At the same time, when the individual would like to change in the opposite direction from what others are suggesting, it is a more nuanced analysis depending on the other system considerations. We will address these in our next and final installment.</p>
<p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/08/applying-facio-behavioural-part-4-gap-alignment-2/">Applying Facio Behavioural, Part 4 &#8211; Gap Alignment</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded>
