		<title>Applying Facio Behavioural, Part 2 &#8211; Realistic Self-Perception</title>
		<link>http://facio.com/blog/2012/08/applying-facio-behavioural-part-2-realistic-self-perception-2/</link>
		<comments>http://facio.com/blog/2012/08/applying-facio-behavioural-part-2-realistic-self-perception-2/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 07 Aug 2012 12:00:37 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Dirk]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[behaviours]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Infovis]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://facio.com/?p=357</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>Continuing the series on analyzing Facio behavioural reports, today we are going to look at Realistic Self-Perception. Considering behavioural results for this requires comparing one&#8217;s self-actual results with the others-actual results provided by those who have worked with them closely. &#8230; <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/08/applying-facio-behavioural-part-2-realistic-self-perception-2/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a></p><p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/08/applying-facio-behavioural-part-2-realistic-self-perception-2/">Applying Facio Behavioural, Part 2 &#8211; Realistic Self-Perception</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Continuing the series on analyzing Facio behavioural reports, today we are going to look at Realistic Self-Perception. Considering behavioural results for this requires comparing one&#8217;s self-actual results with the others-actual results provided by those who have worked with them closely.</p>
<figure style="width: 300px;" class="alignleft"><a href="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/behaviour_work_style.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-497" title="Facio Behaviours - Work Style" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/behaviour_work_style-300x184.jpg" alt="Facio Behaviours - Work Style" width="300" height="184" />Click to view</a></p>
<figcaption>I see myself as somewhat serious at work, and my colleagues agree.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>This comparison helps you understand how realistically they see themselves compared to how others report their behaviour. Criteria where the self-actual and others-actual are identical or within one of one another indicates the individual has a likely realistic self-perception. When the self-actual and others-actual have a difference greater than one but less than three, they likely have a somewhat unrealistic understanding of how they actually are behaving. When the self-actual and others-actual have a difference of three or greater, the individual likely has a significantly unrealistic understanding of how they are actually behaving.</p>
<p>This is a relatively straightforward measure and one that, while it can be combined with other aspects of Facio Behavioural, tells quite a story on its own. Without exception, having a realistic self-perception is a good thing. Even in cases where you or others are dissatisfied with your actual behaviour, simply having an accurate picture of how you actually behave is a powerful and positive thing, reinforcing a basis for successful change, or reflecting a person with strong overall alignment.</p>
<p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/08/applying-facio-behavioural-part-2-realistic-self-perception-2/">Applying Facio Behavioural, Part 2 &#8211; Realistic Self-Perception</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded>
